05689nam a22009495i 9781614512295DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2015374902  a(OCoLC)952798986  a97816145122957 a10.1515/97816145122952doi  a(DE-B1597)179087  a(OCoLC)917873548  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPK1662b.D38 2015 4aPK1662b.D38 2015 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a491.4/452231 aDavid, Anne Boyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDescriptive Grammar of Bangla /cAnne Boyle David; ed. by Thomas J. Conners, Dustin Chacón. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMouton-CASL Grammar Series [MCASL] ;v200tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tSeries Editors’ Preface -- tPreface -- tContents -- tList of Figures. List of Tables -- t1 About this Grammar -- t2 The Bangla Language -- t3 Phonology and Orthography -- t4 Bangla as a South Asian Language -- t5 Nouns -- t6 Pronouns and Other Pro-forms -- t7 Noun Modifiers -- t8 Other Word Classes and Processes -- t9 Verbs -- t10 Syntax -- tReferences Cited -- tA The Digital Grammar -- tB Unicode Representation -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBangla is spoken as the majority language in Bangladesh and the state of West Bengal in India, and as a minority language in several other Indian states. With almost 200 million native speakers, it ranks among the top ten languages in the world in number of speakers. Based on both primary and secondary materials, the CASL Bangla grammar provides comprehensive coverage of the phonology, orthography, morphology, and syntax of Bangla. Plentiful examples of naturally-occurring sentences provide native orthography, Romanization, and morpheme-by-morpheme glossing along with free translations. Unlike many Romanizations of Bangla, our system eschews Sanskritic influence and instead reflects actual Bangla phonology. We also offer comparative information of use to linguists, highlighting features of Bangla shared with the South Asian sprachbund, such as light verb constructions, as well as those that differentiate Bangla from its Indo-Aryan relatives; for example, its unique NP structure.Written in an accessible style from a theory-neutral perspective, this work will be of use to linguistic researchers, language scholars, and students of Bangla. A formal grammar focusing on the morphology is an available companion work.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aBengali languagexGrammar. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aBangla.  aBengali.  aIndo-Aryan Languages.1 aBoyle David, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChacón, Dustin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChacón, Dustin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConners, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConners, Thomas J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConners, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaxwell, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of e